\@writefile{lof}{\setforeignlanguage {english}}
\@writefile{lot}{\setforeignlanguage {english}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.57}{\ignorespaces (a) Per-symbol flop count: Viterbi MLSE grows as $M^L$ while the MLP relay is constant in both $M$ and $L$; at the smallest configuration (BPSK, $L=3$) Viterbi is in fact cheaper per-flop (64 vs.\ 330) -- the MLP's advantage is in scaling, not in absolute cost at the smallest setting. (b) Measured wall-clock inference time (\texttt  {relaynet}'s own Viterbi and MLP implementations, BPSK, $L=3$): the MLP is 30.8$\times $--85.1$\times $ faster across signal lengths 1{,}000--50{,}000 symbols, reflecting a vectorized batched matrix multiply versus an inherently sequential per-symbol trellis scan; this ratio is specific to this numpy/Python implementation, not a universal hardware-independent claim.}}{122}{figure.caption.146}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:supp-complexity}{{A.57}{122}{(a) Per-symbol flop count: Viterbi MLSE grows as $M^L$ while the MLP relay is constant in both $M$ and $L$; at the smallest configuration (BPSK, $L=3$) Viterbi is in fact cheaper per-flop (64 vs.\ 330) -- the MLP's advantage is in scaling, not in absolute cost at the smallest setting. (b) Measured wall-clock inference time (\texttt {relaynet}'s own Viterbi and MLP implementations, BPSK, $L=3$): the MLP is 30.8$\times $--85.1$\times $ faster across signal lengths 1{,}000--50{,}000 symbols, reflecting a vectorized batched matrix multiply versus an inherently sequential per-symbol trellis scan; this ratio is specific to this numpy/Python implementation, not a universal hardware-independent claim}{figure.caption.146}{}}
\newlabel{fig:supp-complexity@cref}{{[figure][57][2147483647,1]A.57}{[1][121][]122}}
